OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Indian Grave Brook at Hardscrabble Rd at Park's Southern Bdy
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The headwaters of Indian Grave Brook are outside of the Park's boundaries.  This brook has a rapid flow with a bottom of large rocks often projecting from the water surface.  The Indian Grave station is the southernmost sampling area of this study.
AquiferName: NA

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Passaic River at Park's Northern Boundary
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The Passaic River is the second longest river in New Jersey.  It is a roving, relatively slow-moving river whose headwaters are in Leddell Pond just outside the boundaries of Morristown National Historical Park.  It is by far the largest of the five water systems in the present study. A remnant of glacial Lake Passaic, this river borders or passes through seven of New Jersey¿s counties before finally draining into Newark Bay.
AquiferName: NA

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Jersey Brook near Park's Southern Bdy next to Tempe Wick Rd.
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Jersey Brook is a small intermittent brook which runs almost parallel to Tempe Wick Road just within the boundary of the Park.  It is the shallowest of our sampling areas and because of the slope of the terrain, it is perhaps the water system most affected by road salts and other contaminants.  Hickory Trees are the abundant tree and the age of the forest is estimated at greater than 60 years.
AquiferName: NA

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: East Primrose Brook Above Cat Swamp Pond
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Both branches of the Primrose Brook are spring fed and have their headwaters within the boundary of Morristown National Historical Park.  The vegetation of the Primrose area is wooded with the dominant trees aged 20 to 60 years.  Species include Chestnut, Hickory, Red Oak, White Oak and Black Oak.  The rate of flow and depth of the water of the sites is variable and both branches of the Primrose Brook tend to be rocky with a sandy bottom.
AquiferName: NA

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
